the deafening silence despite being accepted into this scholarship is quite distressing, visa procedures haven't even started yet. lots can change until Sep/Oct and at the moment there's little I can do than to just hope for the best by then

I can't say how lucky I am to have this option but many others don't. there is talk of stepping down from the scholarship, taking on bank loans, potentially ruining your credit score etc., others are, of course, outright worried and they don't know what to do.

I'm not even kidding if I say that there were moments where I briefly considered either postponing or stepping down from the scholarship because the financial burden is too high. but I have family who are willing to step in should this be the case if nothing changes by September

mind you, this is applying to all MEXT scholarship recipients. we are talking about people coming from SEA, the Middle East etc., and we are probably all advised to bring this much money with us. some countries don't even allow carrying that much money at an airport

under normal circumstances, students are advised to bring at least 2k USD with them to cover expenses for the first month, as the first payment of the scholarship is delayed by one month after arrival. with quarantine, we may be looking at 4k-5k USD in total.

none of the scholars slated to go in Oct have received definite travel dates from their embassies yet, simply because they probably don't really know themselves and the gov hasn't said anything either. worst of all is probably: as of now, we'd have to pay for quarantine

CN: scholarship status, Japan travel bans, financial burdens

This is not to blame teachers but shows how much the German education system has to be improved. Better pay for teachers, a reworked curriculum, giving all students opportunities of proper education.

A big responsibility on how to learn that these are topics still relevant today also falls onto teachers. In high school I can confidently say that only my social sciences teacher really wanted his students to critically think for themselves and always ask questions.

There's a serious disconnect of the things you learn in 'school' and its applications to current topics relevant to racism, classism and so forth. It's kinda like being taught about WW2 and racism, you learn about it in a way as if it's something concluded in the past.

I remember taking the advanced class but learned nothing about the civil rights movement. Instead, it was a lot of Shakespeare which I detested at the time and Aldous Huxley. Which is sort of ironic that we talked about Dystopian novels but never about systemic oppression now. https://t.co/GOnUtr70ta

It’s important to be able to acknowledge an author’s shortcomings but still allow for the text to transform. We shouldn’t make the mistake of attributing this to the author’s skills or their authority over their work. For the reader, the author is both dead and alive.
People can continue cosplaying HP, create content for it and so forth without supporting Rowling directly and that’s okay.

It’s likely the opposite: the last instance of interpretation, the reader, is given a text they can work with and make it even better. With transformative works, creators can act like as if the author is dead – because they have no authority over a reader’s interpretation.
but not part of Rowling’s work. Only because the author is alive, does not mean all the fan created content loses its meaning or is invalid.

with a different perspective altogether. 

Okay, so, the author is not dead. But this does not mean that the author is the single source of interpretation: transformative works in literature, here the HP fandom and its countless fanfiction, is part of Harry Potter

At the same time, when we hold authors accountable, we can also lift others who have a rare voice in literature, such as PoC authors. The author being alive is not a bad thing at all, especially when we can look for those who are otherwise marginalised and give us stories
(thoughtful names for white characters vs. ‘Kingsley Shacklebolt’ / ‘Cho Chang’ for PoC). The author is alive, and they should be accountable for the things they create.

If the author is dead and we remove Rowling or any other author from their book or works, we also remove their responsibility and in this case, her for the anti-Semitic and racist depictions of characters, her ignorance of e.g. giving names to fictional characters

Is the author dead? For years, I thought yes, the author is dead. But lately I have had my doubts about this and now with JK Rowling being a 100% TERF, I treat this question like Schrödinger’s cat. Why?

We can't blame PoCs, immigrants or people with disabilities to not 'make' it at uni, we can't blame them if they seek out other opportunities because the barriers as they are right now are hindering diversity in academia. I wish academia or humanities could do better.

There's so much I could write about, the elitism of students, the sheer inaccessibility of readings that make you feel stupid and dumb for not understanding it, how this is made a 'standard' in academia to sound 'smart' but the truth is that it's a barrier.

I participated in a conference last year and met another PoC in my workshop and I was so thrilled.

I can literally name these encounters I've had with teachers or other students during seven years of studying with the last two actively in academia with one hand.

The one teacher I incredibly admired, an American Korean professor for Media Studies was fired last year and she is now suing my exchange university over power harassment. Academia is hard, even more so when you're PoC

Excluding my exchange year in Tokyo, almost all of the teachers I had were white. And while exchange was an eye-opener in many regards, diversity was still incredibly difficult for PoC. The Humanities teaching staff comprised mostly of American expats and Japanese scholars.

For #DiversityDay, I wish academia was more diverse. From students to teaching staff to administration, my own experience in the Humanities has been quite one-sided and honestly, if it wasn't for Game Studies I wouldn't be in academia at all
